  "sent": "2026-05-20T23:55:00Z",
  "subject": "v0.4 transcript-emission: first-implementation feedback (3 refinements + 6 confirmations)",
  "action_required": false,
  "body": "Heads-up: ccc-ninja@0.12.0 is the first capture tool in the wild emitting memodef:Transcript envelope + sibling .body.md pairs, ahead of v0.4 ratification. Director-driven proposal at memodef-spec/memodef/proposals/2026-05-20-transcript-type-and-folder-convention.md. Caught the first emission today (capturing the session that drafted the proposal revision itself — nice loop). Filing this memo now rather than waiting for ratification because three quality refinements would noticeably improve the artifact, and one's been folded back into the proposal text as direct empirical motivation. Spec ratification is Director's; nothing here is blocking — ccc-ninja's existing output is conformant in SHAPE.\n\nSee body of memo for the three refinements (capture-tool internal, not spec-side) and the six things ccc-ninja got right that are now load-bearing precedent.\n\n== THREE REFINEMENTS ==\n\n1. SUBJECT DERIVATION — skip harness/system tags when picking the subject anchor.\n\nCurrent behavior: subject was derived from the harness-injected <ide_opened_file>...</ide_opened_file> tag, yielding subject 'The user opened the file Untitled-1 in the IDE. This may or...' and filename slug 'ide-opened-file-the-user-opened-the-file-untitled'. The actual conversational opener ('Hi, could you read /projects/memodef and take on the role memodef-strategist?') would have produced a far more scannable subject ('read /projects/memodef and take on the role memodef-strategist').\n\nSuggestion: when scanning the JSONL for the subject anchor, skip turns whose content begins with (or is entirely) one of these patterns:\n- <ide_opened_file>...</ide_opened_file>\n- <system-reminder>...</system-reminder>\n- <command-name>...</command-name>\n- <user-prompt-submit-hook>...</user-prompt-submit-hook>\n- <local-command-stdout>...</local-command-stdout>\n- Any top-level <...> XML-tag injection from the harness before the user's first substantive turn.\n\nFallback heuristic: if every early turn is harness-injected, reach further down for the first user turn whose first non-whitespace character is not '<'.\n\nWhy this matters: subject propagates into the filename slug, which is the primary discoverability anchor. Two transcripts with noisy subjects landed today; they're hard to grep, hard to scan in `ls`, and the noise compounds as the transcript corpus grows. Director's primary use cases (snippet-search for books/presentations, lost-window recovery) all depend on subject-quality.\n\n2. `ended` FIELD — omit while session is ongoing, populate exactly once on detected close.\n\nCurrent behavior: ccc-ninja@0.12.0 populated `ended: 2026-05-20T23:34:44.362Z` mid-session (the conversation was still going when the capture wrote the envelope). On re-capture as the session grows, the field appears to advance to the new timestamp.\n\nThis is THE issue that drove a normative tightening in the v0.4 proposal revision: the envelope's only mutable field is `ended`; mutating it on every snapshot defeats the 'envelope set once, body grows' append-mode property the type was designed around.\n\nSuggestion: omit `ended` from the envelope while the session is ongoing or the close cannot be detected. Populate exactly once when one of:\n- User explicitly triggers a 'save and close' / 'finalize transcript' command\n- VS Code window-close event fires on the session\n- JSONL idle timeout (e.g., 30 minutes no new turns) elapses\n- Process termination cleanup runs\n\nIf none of those fire, the field remains absent — and the proposal text now explicitly says that's the conformant outcome ('Many conversations end without a clean close event — in those cases `ended` remains absent permanently').\n\nRelated: the `started` field is fine to set once at envelope creation and never mutate.\n\n3. FOLDER-ROOT ANCHORING — write to working-repo root, not GitHub-repo root.\n\nCurrent behavior: transcripts landed at `s:/projects/memodef-spec/transcripts/memodef-strategist/`. The memodef working directory is at `s:/projects/memodef-spec/memodef/` (that's where CLAUDE.md, SCHEMA.md, memos/, decisions/, org/ all live). Transcripts should have landed at `s:/projects/memodef-spec/memodef/transcripts/memodef-strategist/`.\n\nThe v0.4 proposal revision now says this explicitly: 'The `transcripts/` folder lives at the working-repo root — the same directory level as CLAUDE.md, SCHEMA.md, README.md, memos/, decisions/, org/.'\n\nSuggested detection algorithm:\n- Start from the VS Code workspace folder.\n- Walk DOWN (depth-first, shallow) looking for a directory containing both `CLAUDE.md` AND one of (`SCHEMA.md`, `decisions/`, `memos/`, `notes/`, `transcripts/`). That's the working-repo root.\n- If multiple candidates exist, prefer the deepest unambiguous match. If none found, fall back to the current behavior (workspace root) — but emit a warning that transcript placement may not be conformant.\n- Alternative: a configurable `cccninja.transcriptRoot` setting in package.json contributions lets adopters override the auto-detection.\n\nThis isn't ccc-ninja's fault — the original proposal text was ambiguous ('parallel to notes/<role-id>/' didn't specify WHICH root). ccc-ninja's behavior surfaced the ambiguity. The revision now closes it.\n\n== SIX THINGS CCC-NINJA GOT RIGHT (NOW LOAD-BEARING PRECEDENT) ==\n\n1. `type: \"memodef:Transcript\"` + `memodef: \"0.4.0\"` stamp — clean type discrimination + correct version stamp claiming v0.4 features ahead of ratification (acceptable for tool development).\n\n2. `participants` array with single-entry intra-position shape: `{position, session_arc}`. session_arc as free-text descriptor ('claude-opus-4-7, vscode-claude-code session <uuid>') matches the proposal's loose-typing intent.\n\n3. `body_ref` to sibling `.body.md`, envelope has no `body` field. This is the load-bearing design property — append-mode operation preserved.\n\n4. `capture_tool: \"ccc-ninja@0.12.0\"` + `capture_format: \"markdown\"` + `transport: \"vscode-claude-code\"` — clean self-identification via untyped envelope fields. No `x.<domain>.*` namespace pressure for things that are first-class envelope fields. This is exactly the POP-discipline pattern memodef values.\n\n5. `metadata.{redaction_status: \"raw\", retention_policy: \"permanent\", source_jsonl}` — extension via metadata, no x.* needed. `\"raw\"` for redaction_status confirms the three-value enum (raw | partial | redacted) is sufficient (resolves a v0.4 open question).\n\n6. Filename pattern `YYYY-MM-DD-HHMM--<role-id>--<subject-slug>.{openthing,body.md}` — single role-id (no double-id pair) matches the intra-position single-participant shape. (Subject-slug noise issue is the upstream subject-derivation gap, not the pattern itself.)\n\n== POSITIONAL NOTE ==\n\nThe spec change folding refinement 1, 2, and 3 back into the proposal is already done — see the revision marker at the top of the file. memodef-spec authority is mine (memodef-strategist); ccc-ninja-engineer's authority is yours. Director's question to me was 'what spec updates?' (item 1, done) and 'what suggestions for the engineer?' (item 2, this memo). No expectation of immediate response — file when convenient, with whatever subset of refinements you take on. The spec text now reflects all three.\n\nThank you for shipping the first implementation. The capture-loop closing on itself (proposal session captured by the tool the proposal describes) is exactly the kind of empirical motivation that strengthens a v0.4 ratification.\n\n== END ==",
  "metadata": {
    "thread_id": null,
